{"title_page": "Larry Pine", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Larry Pine\n| image = Larry Pine 2016.jpg\n| caption = Pine in 2016\n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1945|3|3}}\n| birth_place = [[Tucson, Arizona]], U.S.\n|education = [[University of North Texas]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])}}<br>[[New York University]] {{small|([[Master of Fine Arts|MFA]])}}\n| occupation = Actor\n| years_active = 1968\u2013present\n| spouse = {{marriage|Margaret Rachlin|1969}}\n| children = 1\n}}\n'''Larry Pine''' (born March 3, 1945) is an American actor.\n\nA veteran of the Broadway stage, he began his career playing the role of Fop in the 1968 production of ''[[Cyrano de Bergerac (play)|Cyrano de Bergerac]]''. He has since starred in film and television, with recurring roles in television in ''[[As the World Turns]]'', ''[[One Life to Live]]'', ''[[All My Children]]'', ''[[Hostages (American TV series)|Hostages]]'', ''[[House of Cards (American TV series)|House of Cards]]'', ''[[Succession (TV series)|Succession]]''. He has also appeared in films such as ''[[Vanya on 42nd Street]]'' (1994), [[Tim Robbins]]'s ''[[Dead Man Walking (film)|Dead Man Walking]]'' (1995), ''[[Before and After (film)|Before and After]]'' (1996), ''[[Maid in Manhattan]]'' (2002), [[Woody Allen]]'s ''[[Melinda and Melinda]]'' (2004), and [[Wes Anderson]]'s ''[[The Royal Tenenbaums]]'' (2001), ''[[Moonrise Kingdom]]'' (2012), and ''[[The Grand Budapest Hotel]]'' (2014).\n\n==Career==\nPine began his professional acting career [[Off-Broadway]], then in 1968 appeared as Fop in ''[[Cyrano de Bergerac (play)|Cyrano de Bergerac]]'' at the [[Vivian Beaumont Theater]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://gothamist.com/2013/05/28/interview_with_larry_pine.php| title=Actor Larry Pine Talks Walt Disney, Wallace Shawn, Lemmings| author=John Del Signore| date=May 28, 2013| publisher=Gothamist| access-date=March 24, 2018| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180225073625/http://gothamist.com/2013/05/28/interview_with_larry_pine.php| archive-date=February 25, 2018| url-status=dead}}</ref> A founding member of the avant-garde theater company the Manhattan Project, he appeared in its 1968 production of ''[[Alice in Wonderland]]'', directed by [[Andre Gregory]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.alice150.com/event/whos-alice-an-evening-with-kate-burton-david-del-tredici-larry-pine-and-monica-edinger/| title=Who's Alice: An Evening with Kate Burton, David Del Tredici, Larry Pine, Monica Edinger, and Robert Sabuda| publisher=Alice 150}}</ref>\n\nIn 1978, he made his film debut in [[James Ivory (director)|James Ivory]]'s ''[[Hullabaloo Over Georgie and Bonnie's Pictures]]'',<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.tcm.com/this-month/article/430514%7C412887/Hullabaloo-Over-Georgie-and-Bonnie-s-Pictures.html| title=Hullabaloo Over Georgie and Bonnie\u2019s Pictures| publisher=TCM}}</ref> which was made for television but later released theatrically.{{citation needed|date=February 2016}} Since then, he has performed in [[Louis Malle]]'s ''[[Vanya on 42nd Street]]''<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/10/19/movies/film-review-vanya-on-42d-street-spare-chekhov-begins-sneakily.html| title=Film Review: Vanya on 42d Street; Spare Chekhov Begins Sneakily| author=Janet Maslin| publisher=The New York Times}}</ref> and [[Woody Allen]]'s ''[[Celebrity (film)|Celebrity]]'', ''[[Small Time Crooks]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/larry-pine/video/161301/small-time-crooks-official-trailer-24482065/ |title= Small Time Crooks Official Trailer |publisher=TV Guide}}</ref> and ''[[Melinda and Melinda]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A58609-2005Mar22.html |title= \u2019Melinda and Melinda\u2019: A Tragedy, a Comedy, a Mess |author= Stephen Hunter |date= March 23, 2005 |publisher= Washington Post}}</ref> among other films. Pine appears in the book ''[[Are You Dave Gorman?]]'' as the first actor the writer encounters to have played a fictional Dave Gorman (in ''[[The Ice Storm (film) |The Ice Storm]]'').<ref>{{cite web |url= https://networthpost.com/net-worth/larry-pine-net-worth/ |title= Larry Pine Net Worth |publisher= Net Worth Post}}</ref> In both ''[[The Royal Tenenbaums]]'' and ''[[The Door in the Floor]]'', he appears as a [[Charlie Rose]]-type interviewer, conducting a one-on-one interview in a dark studio.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://i-d.vice.com/en_uk/article/gyj7v7/this-scene-from-the-royal-tenenbaums-is-going-viral-in-light-of-charlie-rose| title=this scene from the royal tenenbaums is going viral in light of charlie rose| author=Hannah Ongley| date=November 22, 2017| publisher=i-D Vice}}</ref> From 1997 to 1999, Pine portrayed Barry Shire #1 on ''[[All My Children]]''.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/person/152680%7C0/Larry-Pine/biography.html| title=Larry Pine| publisher=TCM}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nPine was born in Tucson, Arizona. He received a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree from the [[University of North Texas]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movies/person/56870/Larry-Pine/biography|title=Larry Pine Biography \u2013 Movies & TV|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=February 3, 2016}}</ref> and went on to graduate from [[New York University]]'s [[Tisch School of the Arts]] in 1968 with a [[Master of Fine Arts]] degree.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tisch.nyu.edu/grad-acting/alumni/some-alumni-bios|title=Select Alumni Bios|publisher=[[Tisch School of the Arts]]. [[New York University]]|accessdate=February 3, 2016}}</ref> Since 1969, he has been married to composer and sound designer Margaret Pine (n\u00e9e Rachlin). The couple have one son, Jacob Pine (born 1972).\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Director\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1982\n| ''[[I, the Jury (1982 film)|I, the Jury]]''\n| Movie Director\n| [[Richard T. Heffron]]\n|\n|-\n| 1982\n| ''[[Hanky Panky (1982 film)|Hanky Panky]]'