cLane\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[Empire Falls (miniseries)|Empire Falls]]''\n| Otto Mayer\n| Miniseries; 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit]]''\n| Attorney Van Allen\n| Episode: \"Clock\"\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[Canterbury's Law]]''\n| Wallace Warren\n| Episode: \"What Goes Around\"\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[Person of Interest (TV series)|Person of Interest]]''\n| Wernick\n| Episode: \"Foe\"\n|-\n| 2011\u20132012\n| ''[[Homeland (TV series)|Homeland]]''\n| Richard Halsted\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Blue Bloods (TV series)|Blue Bloods]]''\n| NYPD Chief Surgeon\n| Episode: \"Mother's Day\"\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[The Good Wife]]''\n| Paul Lampard\n| Episode: \"The Seven Day Rule\"\n|-\n| 2013\u20132014\n| ''[[Hostages (American TV series)|Hostages]]''\n| Burton Delaney\n| 10 episodes\n|-\n| 2013\u20132017\n| ''[[House of Cards (American TV series)|House of Cards]]''\n| Bob Birch\n| 23 episodes\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Unforgettable (2011 TV series)|Unforgettable]]''\n| Stanton Ward\n| Episode: \"Til Death\"\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Madam Secretary (TV series)|Madam Secretary]]''\n| Sean Williams\n| Episode: \"Catch and Release\"\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Chicago Med]]''\n| Tom Donovan\n| Episode: \"iNO\"\n|-\n| 2017\u20132018\n| ''[[Gotham (TV series)|Gotham]]''\n| Mayor Burke\n| 3 episodes\n|-\n| 2018\u20132019\n| ''[[Succession (TV series)|Succession]]''\n| Sandy Furness\n| 5 episodes\n|}\n\n==Stage==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1968\n| ''[[Cyrano de Bergerac (play)|Cyrano de Bergerac]]''\n| Fop\n| [[Vivian Beaumont Theater]], [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]]\n|-\n| 1976\n| ''Jinxs Bridge''\n| Elmo Drake\n| [[The Public Theater]], [[Off-Broadway]]\n|-\n| 1977\u201378\n| ''[[The Mandrake]]''\n| Brother Timothy\n| The Public Theater, Off-Broadway\n|-\n| 1983\n| ''[[Private Lives]]''\n| Victor Prynne\n| [[Lunt-Fontanne Theatre]], Broadway\n|-\n| 1984\n| ''End of the World''\n| Ensemble\n| [[Music Box Theatre]], Broadway\n|-\n| 1985\n| ''[[A Day in the Death of Joe Egg]]''\n| Bri / Freddie\n| [[Longacre Theatre]], Broadway\n|-\n| 1993\u201394\n| ''[[Angels in America: A Gay Fantasia on National Themes|Angels in America]]''\n| Roy Cohn\n| [[Walter Kerr Theatre]], Broadway\n|-\n| 1996\n| ''[[Bus Stop (play)|Bus Stop]]''\n| Virgil Blessing\n| [[Circle in the Square Theatre]], Broadway\n|-\n| 2003\n| ''The Women of Lockerbie''\n| Bill Livingston\n| [[The New Group]], Off-Broadway\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Stuff Happens]]''\n| Donald Rumsfeld\n| The Public Theater, Off-Broadway\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''Secret Order''\n| Robert Brock\n| [[Merrimack Repertory Theatre]], Off-Broadway\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 2009\n| ''[[The Royal Family (play)|The Royal Family]]''\n| Gilbert Marshall\n| [[Samuel J. Friedman Theatre]], Broadway\n|-\n| ''[[The Shanghai Gesture]]''\n| Sir Guy Charteris\n| Julia Miles Theater, Off-Broadway\n|-\n| rowspan=3 |2014\n| ''[[Casa Valentina]]''\n| The Judge / Amy\n| Samuel J. Friedman Theatre, Broadway\n|-\n| ''Billy & Ray''\n| Raymond Chandler\n| [[Vineyard Theatre]], Off-Broadway\n|-\n|''A Public Reading of an Unproduced <br/>Screenplay About the Death of Walt Disney''\n|Walt Disney\n|[[Soho Repertory Theater]], Off-Broadway,\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Buried Child]]''\n| Father Dewis\n| The New Group, Off-Broadway\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''Evening at the Talk House''\n| Tom\n| The New Group, Off-Broadway\n|-\n|}\n\n== Awards and Nominations ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Award\n! Category\n! Title\n! Result\n|-\n|1995 || [[Independent Spirit Award]] || [[Independent Spirit Award for Best Supporting Male|Best Supporting Male]] || ''[[Vanya on 42nd Street]]'' || {{nom}}\n|-\n|2001 || [[Joe A. Callaway Award]] || {{n/a}} || ''[[The Seagull]]'' || {{won}}\n|-\n|2014 || [[Obie Award]] || Performance || ''A Public Reading of an Unproduced <br/> Screenplay About the Death of Walt Disney'' || {{won}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Manhattan Project. ''Alice in Wonderland: The Forming of a Company and the Making of a Play'', New York: Merlin House (1973).\n\n==External links==\n\n* {{IMDb name|0683978}}\n* {{IBDB name}}\n* {{iobdb name|460}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pine, Larry}}\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male stage actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Tucson, Arizona]]\n[[Category:Tisch School of the Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:University of North Texas alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Larry Pine\n| image = Larry Pine 2016.jpg\n| caption = Pine in 2016\n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1945|3|3}}\n| birth_place = [[Tucson, Arizona]], U.S.\n|education = [[University of North Texas]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])}}<br>[[New York University]] {{small|([[Master of Fine Arts|MFA]])}}\n| occupation = Actor\n| years_active = 1968\u2013present\n| spouse = {{marriage|Margaret Rachlin|1969}}\n| children = 1\n}}\n'''Larry Pine''' (born March 3, 1945) is an American actor.\n\nA veteran of the Broadway stage, he began his career playing the role of Fop in the 1968 production of ''[[Cyrano de Bergerac (play)|Cyrano de Bergerac]]''. He has since starred in film and television, with recurring roles in television in ''[[As the World Turns]]'', ''[[One Life to Live]]'', ''[[All My Children]]'', ''[[Hostages (American TV series)|Hostages]]'', ''[[House of Cards (American TV series)|House of Cards]]'', ''[[Succession]]''. He has also appeared in films such as ''[[Vanya on 42nd Street]]'' (1994), [[Tim Robbins]]'s ''[[Dead Man Walking (film)|Dead Man Walking]]'' (1995), ''[[Before and After (film)|Before and After]]'' (1996), ''[[Maid in Manhattan]]'' (2002), [[Woody Allen]]'s ''[[Melinda and Melinda]]'' (2004), and [[Wes Anderson]]'s ''[[The Royal Tenenbaums]]'' (2001), ''[[Moonrise Kingdom]]'' (2012), and ''[[The Grand Budapest Hotel]]'' (2014).\n\n==Career==\nPine began his professional acting career [[Off-Broadway]], then in 1968 appeared as Fop in ''[[Cyrano de Bergerac (play)|Cyrano de Bergerac]]'' at the [[Vivian Beaumont Theater]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://gothamist.com/2013/05/28/interview_with_larry_pine.php| title=Actor Larry Pine Talks Walt Disney, Wallace Shawn, Lemmings| author=John Del Signore| date=May 28, 2013| publisher=Gothamist| access-date=March 24, 2018| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180225073625/http://gothamist.com/2013/05/28/interview_with_larry_pine.php| archive-date=February 25, 2018| url-status=dead}}</ref> A founding member of the avant-garde theater company the Manhattan Project, he appeared in its 1968 production of ''[[Alice in Wonderland]]'', directed by [[Andre Gregory]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.alice150.com/event/whos-alice-an-evening-with-kate-burton-david-del-tredici-larry-pine-and-monica-edinger/| title=Who's Alice: An Evening with Kate Burton, David Del Tredici, Larry Pine, Monica Edinger, and Robert Sabuda| publisher=Alice 150}}</ref>\n\nIn 1978, he made his film debut in [[James Ivory (director)|James Ivory]]'s ''[[Hullabaloo Over Georgie and Bonnie's Pictures]]'',<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.tcm.com/this-month/article/430514%7C412887/Hullabaloo-Over-Georgie-and-Bonnie-s-Pictures.html| title=Hullabaloo Over Georgie and Bonnie\u2019s Pictures| publisher=TCM}}</ref> which was made for television but later released theatrically.{{citation needed|date=February 2016}} Since then, he has performed in [[Louis Malle]]'s ''[[Vanya on 42nd Street]]''<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/10/19/movies/film-review-vanya-on-42d-street-spare-chekhov-begins-sneakily.html| title=Film Review: Vanya on 42d Street; Spare Chekhov Begins Sneakily| author=Janet Maslin| publisher=The New York Times}}</ref> and [[Woody Allen]]'s ''[[Celebrity (film)|Celebrity]]'', ''[[Small Time Crooks]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/larry-pine/video/161301/small-time-crooks-official-trailer-24482065/ |title= Small Time Crooks Official Trailer |publisher=TV Guide}}</ref> and ''[[Melinda and Melinda]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A58609-2005Mar22.html |title= \u2019Melinda and Melinda\u2019: A Tragedy, a Comedy, a Mess |author= Stephen Hunter |date= March 23, 2005 |publisher= Washington Post}}</ref> among other films. Pine appears in the book ''[[Are You Dave Gorman?]]'' as the first actor the writer encounters to have played a fictional Dave Gorman (in ''[[The Ice Storm (film) |The Ice Storm]]'').<ref>{{cite web |url= https://networthpost.com/net-worth/larry-pine-net-worth/ |title= Larry Pine Net Worth |publisher= Net Worth Post}}</ref> In both ''[[The Royal Tenenbaums]]'' and ''[[The Door in the Floor]]'', he appears as a [[Charlie Rose]]-type interviewer, conducting a one-on-one interview in a dark studio.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://i-d.vice.com/en_uk/article/gyj7v7/this-scene-from-the-royal-tenenbaums-is-going-viral-in-light-of-charlie-rose| title=this scene from the royal tenenbaums is going viral in light of charlie rose| author=Hannah Ongley| date=November 22, 2017| publisher=i-D Vice}}</ref> From 1997 to 1999, Pine portrayed Barry Shire #1 on ''[[All My Children]]''.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/person/152680%7C0/Larry-Pine/biography.html| title=Larry Pine| publisher=TCM}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nPine was born in Tucson, Arizona. He received a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree from the [[University of North Texas]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movies/person/56870/Larry-Pine/biography|title=Larry Pine Biography \u2013 Movies & TV|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=February 3, 2016}}</ref> and went on to graduate from [[New York University]]'s [[Tisch School of the Arts]] in 1968 with a [[Master of Fine Arts]] degree.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tisch.nyu.edu/grad-acting/alumni/some-alumni-bios|title=Select Alumni Bios|publisher=[[Tisch School of the Arts]]. [[New York University]]|accessdate=February 3, 2016}}</ref> Since 1969, he has been married to composer and sound designer Margaret Pine (n\u00e9e Rachlin). The couple have one son, Jacob Pine (born 1972).\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Director\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1982\n| ''[[I, the Jury (1982 film)|I, the Jury]]''\n| Movie Director\n| [[Richard T. Heffron]]\n|\n|-\n| 1982\n| ''[[Hanky Panky (1982 film)|Hanky Panky]]''\n| Interrogator\n| [[Sidney Poitier]]\n|\n|-\n| 1982\n| ''[[Q (1982 film)|Q]]''\n| The Professor\n| [[Larry Cohen]]\n|\n|-\n| 1982\n| ''MysteryDisc: Murder, Anyone?''\n| Tom Reardon\n| Philip S. Goodman \n| Video\n|-\n| 1982\n| ''[[Alone in the Dark (1982 film)|Alone in the Dark]]''\n| Dr. Harry Merton\n| [[Jack Sholder]]\n|\n|-\n| 1988\n| ''[[Plain Clothes (1988 film)|Plain Clothes]]''\n| Dave Hechtor\n| [[Martha Coolidge]]\n|\n|-\n| 1989\n| ''[[The Dream Team (1989 film)|The Dream Team]]''\n| Canning\n| [[Howard Zieff]]\n|\n|-\n| 1994\n| ''[[Vanya on 42nd Street]]''\n| Dr. Mikhail Astrov\n| [[Louis Malle]]\n|\n|-\n| 1995\n| ''[[Dead Man Walking (film)|Dead Man Walking]]''\n| Guy Gilardi\n| [[Tim Robbins]]\n|\n|-\n| 1996\n| ''[[Before and After (film)|Before and After]]''\n| Dr. Tom McAnally\n| [[Barbet Schroeder]]\n|\n|-\n| 1997\n| ''[[Sunday (1997 film)|Sunday]]''\n| Ben Vesey\n| [[Jonathan Nossiter]]\n|\n|-\n| 1997\n| ''[[The Ice Storm (film)|The Ice Storm]]''\n| Dave Gorman\n| [[Ang Lee]]\n|\n|-\n| 1997\n| ''[[Addicted to Love (film)|Addicted to Love]]''\n| Street Comic\n| [[Griffin Dunne]]\n|\n|-\n| 1997\n| ''Academy Boyz''\n| Ramsey Glover\n| [[Dennis Cooper]]\n|\n|-\n| 1998\n| ''[[Jaded (film)|Jaded]]''\n| Judge Hayfield\n| Caryn Krooth\n|\n|-\n| 1998\n| ''[[Celebrity (film)|Celebrity]]''\n| Philip Datloff\n| [[Woody Allen]]\n|\n|-\n| 1999\n| ''Suits''\n| Peter Haverford\n| [[Eric Weber]]\n|\n|-\n| 1999\n| ''[[Let It Snow (2001 film)|Let It Snow]]''\n| Wendell Milson\n| [[Adam Marcus (director)|Adam Marcus]]\n|\n|-\n| 1999\n| ''A Stranger in the Kingdom''\n| Edward Kinneson\n| [[Jay Craven]]\n|\n|-\n| 2000\n| ''[[Small Time Crooks]]''\n| Charles Bailey\n| [[Woody Allen]]\n|\n|-\n| 2001\n| ''[[The Royal Tenenbaums]]''\n| Peter Bradley\n| [[Wes Anderson]]\n|\n|-\n| 2001\n| ''[[The Shipping News (film)|The Shipping News]]''\n| Bayonet Melville\n| [[Lasse Hallstr\u00f6m]]\n|\n|-\n| 2002\n| ''[[Maid in Manhattan]]''\n| Mr. Lefferts\n| [[Wayne Wang]]\n|\n|-\n| 2003\n| ''[[Particles of Truth]]''\n| Mr. Wiley\n| [[Jennifer Elster]]\n|\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''[[The Clearing (film)|The Clearing]]''\n| Tom Finch\n| [[Pieter Jan Brugge]]\n|\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''[[Melinda and Melinda]]''\n| Max\n| [[Woody Allen]]\n|\n|-\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''[[The Door in the Floor]]''\n| Interviewer\n| [[Tod Williams (filmmaker)|Tod Williams]]\n|\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''Islander''\n| Old Man Cole\n| [[Ian McCrudden]]\n|\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[Killing Kasztner]]''\n| [[Rudolf Kastner|Rudolf Kasztner]]\n| [[Gaylen Ross]]\n|\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''Chasing the Green''\n| Frank Daniels\n| [[Russ Emanuel]]\n|\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[2B (film)|2B]]''\n| Bilko Johnson\n| Richard Kroehling\n|\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[The Good Heart]]''\n| Laugh Therapist\n| [[Dagur K\u00e1ri]]\n|\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Broadway's Finest]]''\n| A. K. Lipson\n| [[Stephen Marro]]\n|\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Arbitrage (film)|Arbitrage]]''\n| Jeffrey Greenberg\n| [[Nicholas Jarecki]]\n|\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[See Girl Run]]''\n| Bob Barrister\n| Nate Meyer\n|\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Moonrise Kingdom]]''\n| Mr. Howard Billingsley\n| [[Wes Anderson]]\n|\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[Jimmy P: Psychotherapy of a Plains Indian]]''\n| [[Karl Menninger]]\n| [[Arnaud Desplechin]]\n|\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[A Master Builder]]''\n| Dr. Ejlert Herdal\n| [[Jonathan Demme]]\n|\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[The Grand Budapest Hotel]]''\n| Mr. Mosher\n| [[Wes Anderson]]\n|\n|-\n